AB  - A new class of Cu6AgBiI10 films has potential application in solar cells and is a lead-free alternative, with inexpensive and unique properties that contribute to the advancement of optical materials. The first time this has been done, a variety of organic (such as spiro-OMeTAD, P3HT, and PEDOT:PSS) and inorganic (such as CuSCN, CuI, and NiOx) hole transport layers (HTLs) with n-i-p structures, Cu6AgBiI10 as absorbers, and (c+mp)TiO2 as electron transport layers (ETLs) were examined in this study, and new approaches to optimizing solar cell devices were explored. The study included simulations and experiments conducted to improve the photovoltaic capabilities of these devices. In this case, hot-casting droplets were poured onto preheated substrates as part of a one-step spin-coating approach. To investigate the structural, optical, and surface morphology features of these films, XRD, UV, and SEM techniques were used along with device simulations for optimizing the photovoltaic performance of the films. It was determined that the performance of the investigated device architectures relies significantly on the thickness of the absorbing layer, the ETL thickness, and the HTL’s thickness as well as the combination of the various HTLs with the device. In addition, the effect of band energy alignment, frequency of capacitance, current density voltage (J-V), quantum efficiency (QE), and generation and recombination rate characteristics was estimated with the help of SCAPS-1D simulation. The best-performing structure with an efficiency of 2.06% is FTO/(c+mp)TiO2/CABI/CuSCN/Au. Additionally, P3HT-, PEDOT:PSS-, spiro-OMeTAD-, CuI-, and NiOx-optimized combinations also showed promising PCE values of 1.28, 1.23, 1.67, 1.72, and 1.54%, respectively. Our findings reveal that HTLs carry a significant influence in maximizing the performance of solar cells. By optimizing the thickness and device structure of solar cells, we were able to maximize the efficiency of the Cu6AgBiI10 film.
