AB  - In this era where technology is upgrading quickly, low operating voltage and low standby power are very important parameters. A tunnel field-effect transistor (TFET) offers efficiency in both these domains. It has a different carrier transport mechanism (different from the MOSFETs) that demands attention. It operates on the principle of quantum science; thus, an understanding of tunneling and the operation of TFET devices with the help of energy band diagrams becomes necessary. A conventional TFET architecture along with the simulation- and fabrication-oriented challenges faced by this device are laid out in this chapter. Simulating a TFET device requires appropriate models that must be incorporated to obtain results that are close to that of the practical scenario. Also, even after a tremendous device is formed using various computer-aided tools, one must take care to ensure its fabrication compatibility. TFET and its multiple mutated structures have been extensively used and grown in the field of biomolecule sensing (biosensing) for the past decade. Therefore, this chapter gives a basic idea of the simulation of a TFET biosensor on a technology computer-aided design (TCAD) tool while drawing some important results and discussions related to its critical performance parameters as well as the sensing metrics. The chapter concludes by discussing the future aspects of TFET devices in the biosensing domain and what measures or improvements can be applied to achieve higher capabilities of TFETs for biomolecule detection.
