AB  - We investigated the bandstructure and transport properties of semiconducting zig-zag b-gallenene nanoribbons (GaNR) using orbitally-resolved Hamiltonians and quantum transport simulations. The impact of GaNR width scaling on the bandstructure, transmission, bandgap and conductance is analyzed in detail. We find that GaNRs exhibit a nontrivial width-dependence of the conductance that is also nonsymmetric for electrons and holes. Moreover, bandgaps of up to ~0.95 eV are achievable by nanoribbon width downscaling. These results are explained by studying the width-dependent evolution of GaNR bandstructure.
