AB  - Quantum key distribution (QKD) enables remote users to share cryptographic keys with information theoretic security. Satellite-to-ground QKD offers a route to extend the distances between users that is otherwise limited by losses through optical fibre. However, satellite QKD is typically limited to operation at night due to the background photons from sunlight. A proposed solution to reduce the background counts is tight spatial filtering via single-mode fibre coupling, but this comes at the cost of losses because of imperfect coupling efficiency due to wavefront distortions from atmospheric turbulence. To maximise the number of photons entering the fibre, adaptive optics (AO) can be used to correct for the atmospheric effects. We present results of end-to-end link simulations which show the trade-off between AO complexity and fibre coupling efficiency. These results show that for representative turbulence characteristics, a relatively small deformable mirror is required to obtain the required coupling efficiency for a reasonable key rate. This paves the way for affordable quantum communication in daylight conditions.
