AB  - The research presents a high-efficiency, eco-friendly perovskite-based solar cell, featuring a novel structure of ITO/ZrO2/CH3NH3SnI3/CuO/Ni. The use of Sn in place of Pb removes toxicity, while the low band gap of the Sn based absorber layer enhances light absorption. CuO, serving as the hole transport layer (HTL), lowers the recombination rate and processing costs compared to the conventional HTL spiro-OMeTAD. ZrO2 is utilized as the electron transport layer (ETL), providing high electron mobility, chemical stability, low cost, and good optical transparency, thereby increasing quantum efficiency across a wider spectrum of light. These innovations result in a power conversion efficiency (PCE) of 24 %. Key performance metrics include an open-circuit voltage (Voc) of 0.80 V, a short-circuit current density (Jsc) of 37.41 mAcm−2, and a fill factor (FF) of 80.2 %. These achievements, optimized using specific resistance and defect density parameters, demonstrate the potential of this solar cell as a low-cost, eco-friendly photovoltaic solution. All simulations were conducted using SCAPS-1D software.
