AB  - In the presented manuscript, we report on the theoretical design and analysis of periodically altered super- lattice alloy-based UV-C Light Emitting Diode (LED) with a specifically developed carrier injection layer. The results show that the intermittently fluctuating strained AlGaN/AlInGaN carrier injection region UV-C LED has better performance over its conventional configuration counterpart due to the enhancement in hole transportation, electron overflow suppression, the reduced polarization effect in quantum wells. By ∼106%, the proposed structure outperforms the traditional design in terms of IQE, according to numerical simulations. The electron potential stature has also enlarged from 263 meV to 451 meV, while the hole potential stature has shortened from 321 meV to 270 meV at 200A-cm-2. The superior electron and hole inoculation in the active area is encouraged by the lowered hole barrier height and increased electron barrier height, which is essential for efficient radiative recombination in the diode.
