AB  - There are two typical interaction geometries that allow for the study of strong field quantum electrodynamics effects: electron-laser and laser-laser collisions. However, the currently available PetaWatt class laser facilities are able to access only the former, because the latter requires much higher laser intensities to observe these effects. Nevertheless, the interaction of electrons and a high-intensity laser provides not only the opportunity to study the multi-photon Compton and Breit-Wheeler effects, but also to characterize the emerging sources of high energy gammas and positrons. Since the BELLA PW laser facility recently commissioned its second laser pulse transport line, this new beamline together with the first beamline can enable electron-laser collision experiments. Here the simulation results showing that experiments will allow the study of laser-particle interactions from the classical to the strong-field quantum electrodynamics regime with a nonlinear quantum parameter of up to χe∼ 2 are presented. In addition, it is demonstrated that the experiments will enable the study and production of GeV-class, mrad-divergence positron beams via the Breit-Wheeler process.
