AB  - Hydrogen has well known and devastating effects on the toughness of high strength steel. It is widely accepted that a detailed theory of hydrogen embrittlement is still lacking. Atomistic modelling of a hydrogen interstitial in α -iron poses enormous challenges. The time scale required to measure the dislocation motion and H diffusivity is usually not accessible in ab initio MD simulations. In addition, in the standard MD implementations, the nuclei behave as classical particles, which for light nuclei such as hydrogen is often a very poor approximation as nuclear quantum effects (NQEs) such as large zero-point energies (ZPE) and quantum tunnelling are neglected. The estimation of nuclear quantum effects on dislocation mobility requires extension of the reach of quantum atomistic simulations to length and time scales relevant for extended defects in materials. Facing this challenge, we develop an external FORTRAN client code, using embedded atom model (EAM) potential to calculate the interatomic interactions in Fe-H system within the framework of ring-polymer molecular dynamics (RPMD).
