AB  - Recently, all inorganic perovskite solar cells have triggered great attention thanks to their rising performance during their development in solid state photovoltaics, showing enhanced characteristics such as good stability, high photoluminescence quantum yield, tunable size, and morphology. In this work, a high open-circuit voltage solar cell based on all-inorganic perovskite through the SCAPS simulator program is presented by analyzing the electron transport layer (ETL), perovskite layer, hole transport layer (HTL) thickness and doping density from an FTO/TiO2/CsPbBr3/Spiro-OMeTAD/Au structure to study its influence on the solar cell performance. From simulation results, it is observed that a thicker ETL hinders carrier transport towards the FTO layer due to the larger distance, which leads to a higher recombination rate, reducing the carrier's lifetime. Albeit high doping density values in ETL enhance the overall solar cell performance. As for the absorber layer, while its thickness increases, the carrier collection rate decreases due to recombination impacting the Vo. Based on the results analysis, the solar cell efficiency improvement is attributed to the built-in electric field as the absorber layer doping density increases. While HTL thickness has minimum impact on the solar cell output, the doping density enhances the proposed device parameters significantly. Summarizing the best results obtained from thickness and doping density simulations, the optimal solar cell operation was 10 nm, 600 nm, and 100 nm layer thicknesses, as well as 1020 cm-3, 1016 cm-3, and 1020 cm-3 doping densities for TiO2, CsPbBr3, and Spiro-OMeTAD, respectively. Results from three different sources, collected from literature, were used to compare and fit them with the simulation program.
