AB  - Quantum network can provide end-to-end entanglements through quantum operations, supporting various quantum applications such as quantum key distribution and distributed quantum computing. However, many previous proposals for quantum networks assumed the division of quantum network into time slots and batch processing of network communication tasks, performing poorly in dynamic network scenarios and not fully utilizing network resources. This work focuses on the routing problem in entanglement quantum networks, aiming to provide more efficient end-to-end entanglement establishment for upper-layer applications. We propose an on-demand routing algorithm that dynamically adjusts the optimal path based on the current network conditions. Specifically, we consider the benefits of path width for quantum networks and propose an algorithm for finding the shortest wide path. Using this algorithm, each node establishes its own routing table. Additionally, to dynamically avoid network hotspots, we introduce the concept of traffic to reflect the busyness of nodes. Finally, using a dynamic cost calculation method as the routing metric, we select the optimal path for the current request. To evaluate the performance of the proposed quantum routing algorithm, we conducted simulation experiments on SimQN quantum simulation platform. The results show that our approach improves network throughput by 14 percent compared to existing solutions.
