AB  - In the present work, the mechanisms of Atmospheric Pressure Chemical Ionisation (APCI) in the air and positive polarity were studied for selected Thiophenes (Thiophene—T, 2-Methylthiophene—2MT, 2,5-Dimethylthiophene—2,5DMT, Benzothiophene—BT and 2-Methylbenzothiophene 2MBT). Using Ion Mobility Spectrometry (IMS) and IMS combined with Mass Spectrometry (IMS-MS) techniques, the reduced ion mobilities of the ions formed via APCI were determined as well as their m/z and structures. The ionisation mechanism was discussed and the limits of detection (LOD) of the substances were determined for IMS. The interpretation of the experimental data was supported by the quantum chemistry simulations of the structure and thermochemical parameters (ionisation energies, proton affinities) of neutral molecules, clusters, and corresponding positive ions.
