AB  - A comprehensive computational study was conducted to investigate the reactive and transport properties of the (Z)-4-Benzylidene-3-methylisoxazol-5(4H)-one molecule. Quantum-mechanical calculations, including density functional theory (DFT) and symmetry-adapted perturbation theory (SAPT), were employed alongside molecular dynamics (MD) simulations using the OPLS4 force field. DFT calculations provided quantum-molecular reactivity descriptors and identified the molecule's most reactive sites. SAPT analysis decomposed interaction energies between pairs of molecules extracted from the crystal structure, revealing the dominant physical contributions to molecular interactions. MD simulations explored the molecule's behavior in an aqueous environment, highlighting the specific atomic interactions with surrounding water molecules. These combined approaches offer detailed insights into the molecule's reactivity, intermolecular interactions, and solvation dynamics, paving the way for future applications in material and chemical sciences.
