AB  - The photogalvanic effect (PGE) has emerged as a promising mechanism for generating photocurrent in 2D materials with broken inversion symmetry. In this study, we systematically investigate the influence of grain boundaries (GBs) on the performance of self-powered photodetectors based on monolayer molybdenum disulfide (MoS2) using quantum transport simulations. Under the illumination of linearly polarized light, we focus on six types of GBs along armchair and zigzag directions, composed of 4|8 and 4|4 membered rings. Within the visible light regime, the theoretical results demonstrate pronounced enhancement of PGE photocurrent in MoS2 monolayer with GBs. The average enhancement ratios for 4|8a/b, 4|8c/d and 4|4a/b GBs are approximately 39, 14, 11, 17, 11 and 22, respectively. The enhancement can be primarily attributed to the reduction of symmetry in the dual-probe device, underscoring the important role of GBs in self-powered 2D photodetectors.
