DO  - 10.1007/s11664-025-11834-6
AB  - Molecular spintronics devices (MSD) offer promising avenues for next-generation computing and memory applications. However, understanding the effect of exchange interactions within molecules involving atomic and electronic spin at different thermal energies remains a critical challenge in the field of MSDs. This study employs Monte Carlo simulations (MCS) to investigate the behavior of magnetic tunnel junction-based molecular spintronics devices (MTJMSDs) across various parameter spaces within a cubic molecule. We examine the dependence of normalized molecular spin (Sm_norm) on intra-molecular biquadratic coupling strength (bm), Heisenberg exchange couplings between neighboring free electrons (Jeem), Heisenberg exchange coupling between fixed atomic spin and free electrons (Je1m and Je0m), and thermal energy (kT). This study investigated the role of biquadratic coupling on molecules with ferromagnetic Heisenberg exchange coupling between the nearest neighboring magnetic atoms of the cubic molecule. We studied the competition effect due to the ferromagnetic Heisenberg coupling and biquadratic coupling aligning the nearest neighbors' spin in parallel and orthogonal directions. Our findings reveal a strong negative correlation between Sm_norm and bm, modulated by temperature and exchange couplings. At lower thermal energies (kT≤0.1), Sm_norm decreases monotonically with increasing bm, indicating molecular spin suppression. Conversely, at higher thermal energies (kT=0.5), a non-monotonic relationship emerges, with Sm_norm peaking at intermediate bm values. This behavior suggests complex collective phenomena at elevated temperatures, possibly due to increased thermal fluctuations enabling intricate local spin-free electron interactions. The exchange couplings Je1m and Jeem further modulate these relationships, particularly at higher thermal energies, underscoring the delicate balance between various interactions in these systems. Our results provide crucial insights into the cumulative effect of free electron and local atomic spins connected by various interactions on overall molecular spin bridged between two ferromagnets. These findings have direct implications for device engineering, where tuning the exchange couplings can enable precise control over spin transport and long-range magnetic ordering. The demonstrated temperature-dependent behavior of molecular spin states suggests the importance of determining optimal operating conditions for future molecular spintronic devices, particularly in memory and quantum computing applications.
