TI  - Probing the biological activity of isatin derivatives against human lung cancer A549 cells: Cytotoxicity, CT-DNA/BSA binding, DFT/TD-DFT, topology, ADME-Tox, docking and dynamic simulations
LA  - eng
JF  - Journal of Molecular Liquids
VL  - 428
PY  - 2025
SN  - 18733166, 01677322
PB  - Elsevier B.V.
DO  - 10.1016/j.molliq.2025.127475
AB  - Isatin derivatives have garnered significant interest due to their diverse pharmacological properties, notably their potent anticancer and antimicrobial properties. These compounds are recognized for their versatility in medicinal chemistry, as they serve as precursors for a wide array of pharmacologically active molecules. To this end, we synthesized two specific derivatives of isatin, including isatin hydrazone and spiro-oxindole in the presence of catalyst, to explore their biological properties through experimental and theoretical studies. The structure of these compounds was characterized using various analytical techniques, including NMR, UV–Vis, and FTIR spectroscopy, supported by theoretical UV–Vis and IR analyses. The cytotoxic potential of these derivatives was evaluated in vitro against A549 human lung carcinoma cell lines using the MTT assay. The interactions of the synthesized isatin derivatives with DNA and bovine serum albumin (BSA) were investigated using UV–Vis spectroscopy and fluorescence titration experiments, targeting DNA as a critical component in cancer therapy and BSA as a major transport protein in the bloodstream. To further explore the molecular properties and chemical behavior of the synthesized compounds, density functional theory (DFT) calculations were performed, including geometry optimization, molecular electrostatic potential (MEP) analysis, HOMO-LUMO orbital investigations, quantum chemical reactivity descriptors, density of states (DOS) spectra, Mulliken charge distribution, and thermodynamic parameter evaluation. Furthermore, topological analyses, including reduced density gradient (RDG) and quantum theory of atoms in molecules (QTAIM), were conducted to elucidate the nature and strength of non-covalent interactions within the compounds. In silico ADME-Tox analysis revealed that the synthesized isatin derivatives exhibit superior drug-likeness, favorable toxicity profiles, and higher drug scores compared to 5-fluorouracil (5-FU), underscoring their potential as promising therapeutic candidates. Finally, molecular docking and dynamic simulation studies further corroborated the anticancer potential of these compounds, reinforcing their suitability for further development as therapeutic agents.
