TI  - Cavity Quantum Electrodynamics Complete Active Space Configuration Interaction Theory
LA  - eng
JF  - Journal of Chemical Theory and Computation
VL  - 20
IS  - 3
SP  - 1214
EP  - 1227
PY  - 2024
SN  - 15499626, 15499618
PB  - American Chemical Society
DO  - 10.1021/acs.jctc.3c01207
AB  - Polariton chemistry has attracted great attention as a potential route to modify chemical structure, properties, and reactivity through strong interactions among molecular electronic, vibrational, or rovibrational degrees of freedom. A rigorous theoretical treatment of molecular polaritons requires the treatment of matter and photon degrees of freedom on equal quantum mechanical footing. In the limit of molecular electronic strong or ultrastrong coupling to one or a few molecules, it is desirable to treat the molecular electronic degrees of freedom using the tools of ab initio quantum chemistry, yielding an approach we refer to as ab initio cavity quantum electrodynamics, where the photon degrees of freedom are treated at the level of cavity quantum electrodynamics. Here, we present an approach called Cavity Quantum Electrodynamics Complete Active Space Configuration Interaction theory to provide ground- and excited-state polaritonic surfaces with a balanced description of strong correlation effects among electronic and photonic degrees of freedom. This method provides a platform for ab initio cavity quantum electrodynamics when both strong electron correlation and strong light-matter coupling are important and is an important step toward computational approaches that yield multiple polaritonic potential energy surfaces and couplings that can be leveraged for ab initio molecular dynamics simulations of polariton chemistry.
ER  -

TY  - JOUR
AU  - Wang, Zikang
AU  - Ikegami, Hiroki
TI  - A Channel Geometry of An Ion Pool for the Study of Vortex Nucleation in Superfluid 4He
LA  - eng
JF  - Journal of Low Temperature Physics
PY  - 2024
SN  - 15737357, 00222291
PB  - Springer
DO  - 10.1007/s10909-024-03232-9
AB  - Superfluidity in liquid 4He is characterized by the absence of viscosity, and the critical velocity marks the transition from a non-dissipative to a dissipative flow state. In past experiments, the critical velocity was observed for a pool of positive ions trapped below a free surface, which was attributed to the nucleation of a quantized vortex associated with the macroscopic quantum tunneling. To study the problem further, here we consider a novel ion pool design in which a channel is connected to reservoirs at both ends and examine the response of the system in both linear and nonlinear regimes (i.e., below and above the critical velocity, respectively) using finite element method (FEM) simulations. We find that the velocity in the channel is uniform within 5% and that the response of the system is well described by the lumped constant circuit model in both linear and nonlinear regimes. These features allow well-controlled investigations of the transport properties of the ions even above the critical velocity, which enables us to quantitatively understand the vortex nucleation process and the vortex state above the critical velocity.
ER  -

TY  - THES
AU  - Mamun, Fahad Al
TI  - Characterization, Analysis, and Modeling of 22nm FD-SOI Technology for Cryogenic Computing and Charge Trap Memory
LA  - eng
PY  - 2024
PB  - ProQuest Dissertations & Theses
AB  - The persistent demand for faster and more energy-efficient computing has pushed traditional CMOS scaling towards its limits. This dissertation explores the potential of 22 nm Fully Depleted Silicon-On-Insulator technology (FD-SOI) to address this challenge, particularly for cryogenic computing applications that require extremely low temperatures. The advantages of operating CMOS circuits at cryogenic temperatures include reduced leakage currents, improved subthreshold swings, and enhanced carrier mobility. This research investigates the electrical characteristics of 22nm FD-SOI devices at cryogenic temperatures by examining the impact on key device parameters. Furthermore, FD-SOI technology offers an additional technological knob, i.e., back-gate bias that can manipulate the carrier concentration and position of charge carriers along the channel thickness. The impact of back-gate bias on the carrier transport in FD-SOI devices was also investigated experimentally and was validated theoretically through quantum mechanical simulation approach by solving Schrödinger-Poisson equation self-consistently. This dissertation also investigates the potential for compact model development by first modifying the MIT virtual source model to validate FD-SOI device performance at cryogenic temperatures and back-gate biases. Later, a new full scale multi-valley model was developed to account for the quantum confinement and carrier degeneracy effects on mobility and injection velocity.This dissertation also explores charge trapping transistors (CTTs) for non-volatile memory applications. The research provides insights into the degradation of carrier transport due to conventional device programming approach resulting in hot carrier injection which is unlikely to recover with erasing method. It has been shown in this dissertation theoretically that for accurate implementation of dot product and vector matrix multiplication, mobility degradation also needed to be considered alongside threshold voltage.This research explores different challenges aiming to pave the way for the development of physics-based models for cryogenic CMOS circuits, specifically in the context of 22nm FD-SOI technology not only for cryogenic computing but also for a broader range of applications.
ER  -

