AB  - We describe a method of duty cycle engineering in optical lattice clocks to reduce clock instability through tailoring of the Dick effect noise contribution. We apply dynamically decoupled interrogation sequences to realise an estimated improvement in single clock instability approaching a factor of two, as well as providing a route to zero dead-time operation for two interleaved clocks which are otherwise unable to reach the required duty cycle. We show through simulations and synchronous measurements of clocks NPL-Sr1 and NPL-Sr2 that a quantum projection noise limited instability < 3 - 10-17τ-1/2 can be realised in a near ideal zero dead-time configuration.
