TY  - THES
AU  - Zeng, Yiming
TI  - Efficient Entanglement Distribution Over Quantum Networks
LA  - eng
PY  - 2024
PB  - ProQuest Dissertations & Theses
AB  - Quantum networks represent the next frontier in communication and computing technologies, leveraging the principles of quantum information science to enable unprecedented capabilities. Unlike classical networks, quantum networks utilize quantum mechanisms to transmit and process information with remarkable efficiency and security. The unique properties of quantum systems, such as superposition and entanglement, allow for tasks infeasible with classical systems, including secure information transmission, quantum sensing, and quantum computing. Effective entanglement routing is crucial for optimizing the performance and reliability of quantum networks. However, efficiently distributing entanglement in these networks presents significant technical challenges, necessitating innovative approaches that consider the unique characteristics of quantum information.This dissertation delves into the entanglement routing problem, proposing new methodologies and protocols to enhance the efficiency of entanglement in quantum networks. We explore the design and implementation of entanglement routing algorithms tailored to the unique properties of quantum networks.First, we investigate the two-user entanglement case to simultaneously maximize the number of quantum-user pairs and their expected throughput using the classical swapping method based on Bell State Measurements (BSMs). We approach this by formulating the problem as two sequential integer programming problems. We then propose efficient entanglement routing algorithms for these optimization problems and analyze their time complexity and performance bounds.Second, we consider a more general and efficient swapping method, namely n-fusion based on Greenberger-Horne-Zeilinger (GHZ) measurements, which can fuse n successful entanglement links to maximize the entanglement rate for multiple quantum-user pairs over a quantum network. We propose efficient entanglement routing algorithms that leverage the properties of n-fusion for quantum networks with general topologies.Third, we tackle the fundamental problem of multi-user entanglement routing in quantum networks, aiming to entangle multiple quantum users with a high entanglement rate. We abstract this problem as a novel graph routing problem, which existing graph problem solutions do not readily address due to the unique characteristics of the quantum network. To address this, we first consider a sufficient condition ensuring the existence of a feasible solution and design an algorithm to find the optimal solution. Given the NP-completeness and NP-hardness of determining a feasible solution's existence and deriving an optimal solution in general cases, respectively, we propose two heuristic algorithms to offer efficient solutions. Our research reveals that the quantum network's properties introduce novel challenges and opportunities, bridging classical graph theory with quantum networking through the formulation of new research problems.Through comprehensive theoretical analyses, algorithm design, and extensive simulations, we validate the effectiveness of our proposed solutions. The findings of this dissertation not only enhance the theoretical understanding of entanglement efficiency in quantum networks but also pave the way for future practical applications involving coordinated entangled quantum users.
ER  -

TY  - JOUR
AU  - Mahammedi, Nassim
TI  - Efficient inverted HTL-free Sm$_2$NiMnO$_6$-based perovskite solar cell:
  a SCAPS-1D study
LA  - und
PY  - 2024
AB  - The transition to sustainable energy has accelerated research into perovskite
solar cells (PSCs) as promising candidates for next-generation photovoltaics.
Despite their remarkable efficiencies, the commercialization of PSCs is
hindered by lead toxicity and material instability. In this study, we explore a
lead-free Samarium-based double perovskite oxide Sm$_2$NiMnO$_6$ (SNMO), as the
active absorber layer in an innovative inverted HTL-free PSC architecture.
Using SCAPS-1D simulations, we optimized the device configuration to achieve a
power conversion efficiency (PCE) of 10.93% with an open-circuit voltage (VOC)
of 0.8 V, a short-circuit current density (JSC) of 16.46 mA/cm2, and a fill
factor (FF) of 82.14%. We demonstrate that increasing the SNMO absorber
thickness enhances light harvesting in the red spectrum region (~620 nm),
shifting the external quantum efficiency (EQE) peak from 380 nm at 50 nm
thickness to about 620 nm at 1 um. We also investigated various electron
transport layers (ETLs) and found that the indium tin oxide (ITO) exhibited
superior PV performances, boosting the PCE to ~12.6% due to its excellent
conductivity and optimal energy band alignment with SNMO. These findings
establish SNMO as a promising absorber material for environmentally friendly
PSCs, paving the way for cheaper, simpler, scalable, and sustainable
photovoltaic solutions. This work highlights the potential of HTL-free
architectures in reducing costs and complexities while maintaining competitive
efficiencies, offering a significant step forward in advancing lead-free solar
technologies.
ER  -

