AB  - The cellulose insulation pressboard is responsible for the main insulation task of the oil-immersed transformers. The prolonged exposure to the electrical and thermal environment inside the transformer results in a decline in the electrical performance of the oil-immersed pressboard. Currently, there is significant research interest in utilising nano-modification technologies to enhance the electrical performance of cellulose insulation. This article investigates the impact of nano-SiO2 modification on the electrical properties of the cellulose insulation pressboard in the electric and thermal fields. Established unmodified and modified cellulose molecular models. Cellulose molecule model was subjected to quantum dynamics simulations. We obtained a comparison of the energy gap, electrostatic potential, Raman spectroscopy, and infrared spectroscopy for unmodified and modified cellulose molecular models. A temperature-controlled measurement platform for the distribution of space charges under direct current (DC) voltage has been established. In order to assess the impact of nano-SiO2 particles, the space charge buildup and dissipation properties of unmodified and modified cellulose insulation pressboards were compared. The findings indicate that due to the coupling effect of electric and thermal fields, the energy gap of the cellulose molecular model modified by the nano SiO2 is larger, more hydrogen bonds are formed, the system is more stable, the polarisation and dipole moment changes of the molecules are smaller, and the dielectric performance is superior. Compared with an unmodified pressboard, a modified pressboard has a lower maximum field distortion rate, a faster space charge dissipation rate, and lower carrier mobility. When exposed to an electric thermal coupling field, including nano-SiO2 particles into the cellulose insulation pressboard enhances its electrical performance.
ER  -

