LA  - eng
JF  - Drug Delivery Systems Using Quantum Computing
SP  - 93
EP  - 139
PY  - 2024
SN  - 1394159145, 1394159323, 1394159331, 9781394159147, 9781394159321, 9781394159338
PB  - wiley
DO  - 10.1002/9781394159338.ch4
AB  - Nano-based therapeutics are the outcome of applying nanotechnology in therapy that resulted in a combined advantage of enhanced drug delivery efficiency and targeted delivery. Along with the advantages, there are challenges to targeted delivery due to the size of the drug delivery system and the complex in vivo vascular system. To efficiently develop nanotherapeutics and deliver its benefits, it is imperative to understand the complex processing of developing nanotherapeutics. Designing the optimal process is necessary to understand the nano-based therapeutic’s targeted delivery mechanism. With the quantum computational simulation models, application in the complex processes of nano-based therapeutic research and development was believed to have the potential to revolutionize the nano-based pharma industry. Quantum computational modeling was estimated to have a drastic impact on the understanding of complex biological processes, solubility enhancement of drugs, drug-excipient compatibility, drug encapsulation, drug release, nanoparticle targeting, drug delivery and uptake, pharmacodynamics, and pharmacokinetics. The quantum computational models for the determination and distribution of nanocarriers in the body followed by systemic administration in various routes, models for visualizing the drug release, optimizing the drug carrier design, drug distribution in the body over time, transportation of the contents of drug product across the compartments in the human body, and how they negotiate with the body’s defense system are the priorities for the design of nanotherapeutics. The final critical step requires models to predict the risk factors and analyze the benefits of nano-based therapeutics in the hope of reducing the number of extensive and expensive clinical trials, if not totally avoiding them. Thus, quantum computational simulation is envisaged to be able to shorten the drug development timelines and lower the risk of failure. The present chapter discusses the role of quantum computational models (coarse-grained, molecular dynamics, particle-based, and physiologically based pharmacokinetic), providing deep insight into the design of nano-based therapeutics.
ER  -

