VL  - 32
IS  - 19
SP  - 33423
EP  - 33441
PY  - 2024
SN  - 10944087
PB  - Optica Publishing Group (formerly OSA)
DO  - 10.1364/OE.531996
AB  - The integration of the continous-variable quantum key distribution(CVQKD) system is an important technical route with great potential value for constructing high-performance and low-cost CVQKD system. In all previous CVQKD studies, the quantum efficiency of the detector can be calibrated in advance and is considered to remain unchanged. But when the size of the system shrinks to the on-chip level, especially in the premise of non-uniform waveguide, heavy doping and other factors, effects such as free carrier absorption and scattering loss will become prominent, which will directly cause carriers undergo violent migration due to the tiny jitter of the local oscillator and further lead to dynamical variation of quantum efficiency of detection. In this paper, we propose a practical chip-based detector model, and numerous simulation results based on this model show that the practical system will face potential security threats due to the variable quantum efficiency. Moreover, two defense strategies are proposed to solve these practical security problems commonly exist in general chip-based CVQKD systems. This work breaks the inherent viewpoint that the quantum efficiency in the chip-based CVQKD system can still be calibrated in advance, and suggests a more rigorous consideration of practical security for development of chip-based CVQKD.
ER  -

TY  - CHAP
TI  - Foreword
LA  - eng
JF  - De Gruyter Ebooks
PY  - 2024
PB  - De Gruyter
DO  - 10.1515/9783111398433-201
AB  - Yang-Mills theory, a concept in physics, extends Maxwell's equations to explain the weak and strong forces within subatomic particles using geometric structures or quantum field theory.This theory depends on a quantum mechanical attribute known as the "mass gap."In a renowned paper from 1954, Yang and Mills proposed a broad range of classical field theories influenced by electromagnetism and satisfying a generalized form of gauge symmetry.Once quantized, these Yang-Mills theories became pivotal in advancing particle physics.Examples of quantized Yang-Mills theories encompass crucial physical theories like quantum electrodynamics, the electroweak theory, the standard model of particle physics, and grand unified theories (GUTs).The laws of quantum physics govern the behavior of elementary particles, akin to how Newton's laws govern the macroscopic world.Yang and Mills introduced a novel framework that employs structures found in geometry to depict elementary particles.Quantum Yang-Mills theory now underpins most elementary particle theories, with its predictions tested in various experimental laboratories.However, its mathematical foundation remains ambiguous.The successful utilization of Yang-Mills theory to elucidate the strong interactions of elementary particles hinges on a subtle quantum mechanical trait termed the "mass gap": quantum particles possess positive masses, despite being classical waves traveling at the speed of light.While physicists have detected this property through experimentation and confirmed it via computer simulations, its comprehension from a theoretical standpoint remains elusive.Progress in establishing the existence of Yang-Mills theory and a mass gap necessitates the introduction of groundbreaking concepts in both physics and mathematics.This book presents a fresh approach to Yang-Mills theory by replacing infinity with observers, termed the "Mathematics with Observers" theory.It addresses current issues surrounding Yang-Mills equations and the existence of the mass gap within this new framework.In essence, Mathematics with Observers reimagines the fundamental principles of arithmetic, Euclidean and non-Euclidean geometries, calculus, functional analysis, Lie groups and algebras, rejecting the concept of infinity and recalibrating all physical calculations into a nested set of observable arithmetic.Hence, it is highly recommended to review previously published work to enable ease of understanding of the material.
ER  -

