AB  - During transportation of shale gas, carbon steel faces corrosion from CO2 and bacteria. Developing inhibitors that can both prevent corrosion and inhibit bacterial growth is of great significance for the protection of shale gas transportation pipelines. In this work, the corrosion inhibition performance of a morpholine Gemini surfactant (BDHM) and its monomer (DHM) was studied in CO2-saturated 5 wt% NaCl solution by weight loss, electrochemical measurements and surface analysis. The antibacterial effect was confirmed through suspension antibacterial experiments. The results showed that BDHM represents a better inhibitory effect than DHM. To investigate the corresponding reason caused by molecular structure, the quantum chemical calculations and molecular dynamics (MD) simulations were carried out, which indicate that the two head groups bring BDHM stronger adsorption capacity, while the two long alkyl chains are more effective in isolating corrosive medium.
