PB  - Elsevier B.V.
DO  - 10.1016/j.physb.2024.416379
AB  - The study investigates the fascinating phenomenon of quantum transport in a single-layer curved graphene superlattice, considering out-of-plane deformations. By employing the Dirac equation in curved space, the research explores the intricate interplay between geometry and quantum mechanics, revealing how structural deformations affect electronic transport properties. The focus is on two periodic deformation examples, providing valuable insights into the influence of curvature-induced modifications on the electronic band structure and highlighting the enhanced transmission coefficients that arise. The periodic deformations serve as a mechanism for tuning and optimizing transmission properties by carefully adjusting deformation parameters. Numerical simulations underscore the substantial impact of structural parameters on quantum transport. Notably, the length of the curved graphene region significantly influences the transmission coefficients. Additionally, the study identifies the incident angle and barrier number as crucial factors in shaping the system's response to external stimuli. By manipulating the incident angle and fermion energy, researchers can modulate transmission properties and control the system's behavior for specific applications.
